---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import HelpCallout from "../../components/HelpCallout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Signs & screening"
  description="Warning signs of gambling harm, and short, validated questions that can help you decide whether to reach out."
>
  <header class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="page-header__eyebrow">
        <a href="/understand-gambling">← Understand gambling</a>
      </p>
      <h1>Signs &amp; screening</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        Noticing the signs early — in yourself or someone you care about — makes
        it easier to get help before the harm grows.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>Warning signs</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Spending more time or money gambling than planned</li>
        <li>Being secretive about money, or money going missing</li>
        <li>Borrowing money or selling things to gamble or to cover losses</li>
        <li>Betting more to feel the same excitement</li>
        <li>Feeling restless or irritable when not gambling</li>
        <li>Returning to win back losses</li>
        <li>Mood that rises and falls with wins and losses</li>
        <li>Letting work, school, or relationships slip</li>
        <li>Lying about gambling</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Quick screening</h2>
      <p>
        Researchers have created short questionnaires — like the Brief Biosocial
        Gambling Screen — that ask just a few questions to flag whether gambling
        may be a problem. A screen is a starting point, not a diagnosis. If a few
        answers raise a flag, it is worth talking to a professional, who can do a
        full assessment.
      </p>
      <p>
        You can find validated screening tools and connect to help through the
        <a href="https://www.ncpgambling.org/help-treatment/">National Council on Problem Gambling</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>What to do next</h2>
      <p>
        The simplest next step is to talk to someone. Call or text the National
        Problem Gambling Helpline — it is free, available 24/7, and can connect you
        to local resources. If money worries or distress feel like a crisis, call
        or text <a href="tel:988">988</a>.
      </p>

      <HelpCallout />

      <div class="sources">
        <h2>Learn more</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="https://www.ncpgambling.org/help-treatment/">NCPG — Help &amp; Treatment, screening tools</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
